WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:24.000
We're now going to talk about some interesting laws and regulations that you may have to

00:24.000 --> 00:27.320
think about as a security professional from around the world.

00:27.320 --> 00:32.320
We're going to start with some interesting, kind of more historical laws related to cryptography.

00:32.320 --> 00:37.480
Then we're going to talk about something known as the Wasson Arrangements and then some

00:37.480 --> 00:39.840
trans-border data flow laws or data residency laws.

00:39.840 --> 00:42.480
But let's start here with this kind of historical footnote.

00:42.480 --> 00:45.600
So here's a really interesting bit of historical trivia.

00:45.600 --> 00:51.240
I'm going to take us back to sort of the late 70s, early 80s.

00:51.240 --> 00:57.000
Back then, some amazing new cryptographic techniques and algorithms we're being developed.

00:57.000 --> 01:00.320
It's like des the data encryption standard that we'll talk about.

01:00.320 --> 01:05.000
And things like asymmetric cryptography, which would solve the symmetric key distribution

01:05.000 --> 01:06.000
problem.

01:06.000 --> 01:07.000
We'll get into all that later.

01:07.000 --> 01:11.400
But these new cryptographic techniques were amazing.

01:11.400 --> 01:13.320
And you could do some really incredible things with them.

01:13.320 --> 01:19.760
You could encrypt information in such a way that no one, no one, could decrypt it.

01:19.760 --> 01:26.480
And this was rather troubling to certain organizations, agencies, like the NSA.

01:26.480 --> 01:28.800
The national security agency in the US.

01:28.800 --> 01:30.920
And so certain laws were put in place.

01:30.920 --> 01:32.920
So here is the fear, right?

01:32.920 --> 01:36.640
Certain governments around the world were concerned that, hey, if someone were to encrypt

01:36.640 --> 01:42.960
information with these new cryptographic techniques, we say the NSA would not be able to decrypt

01:42.960 --> 01:43.960
it.

01:43.960 --> 01:46.520
We don't have, they didn't have the technology to decrypt it.

01:46.520 --> 01:48.280
And that was obviously very troubling to them, right?

01:48.280 --> 01:49.280
Because they're job.

01:49.280 --> 01:51.840
Well, for, you know, there's a lot of agencies around the world, not just the NSA.

01:51.840 --> 01:54.800
And I should probably stop saying NSA because they're probably going to be able to find

01:54.800 --> 01:55.800
me.

01:56.080 --> 02:01.240
So the point is there are certain agencies, governments around the world that wanted

02:01.240 --> 02:07.000
to restrict these cryptographic algorithms and make sure that they didn't get into sketchy

02:07.000 --> 02:11.440
hands, like, I don't know, sketchy Canadians like me.

02:11.440 --> 02:15.920
So certain laws were put in place to restrict the export of cryptographic algorithms.

02:15.920 --> 02:19.640
And there's two of these laws that you need to know about, ITAR and EAR.

02:19.640 --> 02:23.040
Here's the sort of simple thing you have to remember about them.

02:23.040 --> 02:26.760
So ITAR stands for the International Traffic and Arms Regulations.

02:26.760 --> 02:30.960
By the way, these are both US-centric regulations.

02:30.960 --> 02:36.520
ITAR, here's the key thing I remember, focuses on defense-related items.

02:36.520 --> 02:41.720
In other words, technology systems that are specifically meant for defense.

02:41.720 --> 02:43.840
That's what ITAR focuses on.

02:43.840 --> 02:48.360
And so certain cryptographic algorithms might fall under that category of only being used

02:48.360 --> 02:51.200
by defense, and therefore they'd be covered by ITAR.

02:51.680 --> 02:58.120
EAR, the export administration regulations, they cover what are called dual use items.

02:58.120 --> 03:02.240
Dual use items are things, technologies, systems, night vision goggles.

03:02.240 --> 03:04.960
Night vision goggles can be used by the military.

03:04.960 --> 03:08.600
They can also be used by people in regular day lives, although I don't know why you're

03:08.600 --> 03:10.520
wondering on night vision goggles.

03:10.520 --> 03:14.520
But there are certain technologies that are used systems, technologies that are used

03:14.520 --> 03:17.440
both by the military and by civilians.

03:17.440 --> 03:19.720
And that's what are considered to be dual use items.

03:19.720 --> 03:22.320
And EAR covers dual use items.

03:22.320 --> 03:26.880
Simple way to remember this, ITAR covers defense stuff, EAR covers defense and everything

03:26.880 --> 03:27.880
else.

03:27.880 --> 03:29.560
It's kind of the way to think about it.

03:29.560 --> 03:30.880
So these were really serious laws.

03:30.880 --> 03:35.440
If you were found to be in violation of these laws, then you could be thrown in federal

03:35.440 --> 03:36.440
prison.

03:36.440 --> 03:37.760
It was pretty significant.

03:37.760 --> 03:40.920
And these laws were expanded to cover cryptographic systems.

03:40.920 --> 03:46.560
And so back in the kind of 80s, there was certain famous cryptographers that were actually

03:46.800 --> 03:47.560
worried.

03:47.560 --> 03:50.400
It was looking concerningly like they were going to end up in federal prison because they

03:50.400 --> 03:55.440
were creating these algorithms and wanting to put them out in the world.

03:55.440 --> 03:59.680
Now the reason these laws are still in place, but the reason they're not really applicable

03:59.680 --> 04:04.200
anymore is that nowadays the absolute best algorithms that we use, like say the advanced

04:04.200 --> 04:07.320
encryption standard, which we'll talk about later.

04:07.320 --> 04:09.200
It's an open source algorithm.

04:09.200 --> 04:11.160
Everyone has access to it around the world.

04:11.160 --> 04:14.920
And in fact, that's why we trust it so much because it's an open source algorithm.

04:14.920 --> 04:18.720
Most of the thousands of cryptographers around the world have all looked at AES, studied

04:18.720 --> 04:21.800
it, and no one's found a significant vulnerability in it.

04:21.800 --> 04:23.800
And that's why we trust it so much.

04:23.800 --> 04:28.040
And so the best algorithms and encryption algorithms that we use nowadays are open source,

04:28.040 --> 04:30.840
which is why these laws are not really applicable anymore.

04:30.840 --> 04:31.840
They're not really enforced.

04:31.840 --> 04:34.440
So it's a bit of a historical relic, but there you go.

04:34.440 --> 04:37.080
You might come across ITAR or EAR on the exam.

04:37.080 --> 04:39.040
Not super important topic.

04:39.040 --> 04:43.880
One more not super important topic is something known as the wassinar arrangement.

04:43.880 --> 04:48.200
This is a keyword here, voluntary regime.

04:48.200 --> 04:55.200
So there's 42 signing members, 42 countries that got together, and they signed this arrangement.

04:55.200 --> 05:00.040
And the whole point of this is that they are meant to exchange information, primarily related

05:00.040 --> 05:02.520
to arms, weapons, things like that.

05:02.520 --> 05:06.640
And the whole purpose is, as you can see here, wassinar aims to promote greater responsibility

05:06.640 --> 05:11.480
among its members to, in exports of weapons and dole use goods, than to prevent destabilizing

05:11.480 --> 05:12.480
communications.

05:12.480 --> 05:17.560
So basically, these 42 signing members, these 42 countries, are exchanging information

05:17.560 --> 05:21.000
about what sort of weapons and systems they're developing.

05:21.000 --> 05:22.880
And they're trying to be open and transparent about this.

05:22.880 --> 05:26.400
So there isn't concerns that, oh, this country might be building up a big stockpile over

05:26.400 --> 05:30.560
here, but maybe they aren't, they're meant to share information.

05:30.560 --> 05:34.520
Not super important, but it does sometimes the wassinar arrangement sometimes is mentioned

05:34.520 --> 05:35.520
on the exam.

05:35.520 --> 05:39.960
So now you know what it is, voluntary regime between 42 signing members.

05:39.960 --> 05:45.320
Wassinar is a little town in the Netherlands, and it was in this little town in the Netherlands

05:45.320 --> 05:50.840
that all of these 40, where the summit was, where these 42 delegations of these 42 countries

05:50.840 --> 05:52.480
got together and signed this arrangement.

05:52.480 --> 05:56.800
So that's why it's called the wassinar arrangement, not super important.

05:56.800 --> 06:02.000
What we are going to talk about now is very important, and very pertinent to today's

06:02.000 --> 06:03.000
world.

06:03.000 --> 06:07.200
And these are what we're now going to talk about are trans-border, data flow, or data residency,

06:07.200 --> 06:09.120
or data localization laws.

06:09.120 --> 06:10.120
They have these different names.

06:10.120 --> 06:18.120
They're all the same exact concept, which is these laws are designed to prevent the flow

06:18.120 --> 06:22.400
of data across physical borders.

06:22.400 --> 06:26.000
So for instance, I'm from the province of British Columbia.

06:26.000 --> 06:31.400
There's a trans-border data flow law here in BC related to ensuring that BC residents

06:31.400 --> 06:36.560
data, any resident on the government stores on BC residents remain on systems that are

06:36.560 --> 06:43.480
in BC and not, say, transferred down and stored on servers south of us in the US.

06:43.480 --> 06:44.480
Why?

06:44.480 --> 06:49.160
Well, because the government here believes that they have a responsibility to protect

06:49.160 --> 06:50.480
the citizens data.

06:50.480 --> 06:55.080
And if that data was to be stored in systems and say the US, there may not be the same privacy

06:55.080 --> 06:58.240
laws and regulations in place to protect that data.

06:58.240 --> 07:02.040
And so, and this is one of the major reasons that all sorts of different countries around

07:02.040 --> 07:03.400
the world are doing this.

07:03.400 --> 07:06.080
The poster child of this is the European Union.

07:06.080 --> 07:11.440
The European Union's overarching privacy directive, which is known as GDPR.

07:11.440 --> 07:20.120
It has a very stringent data residency requirement in it, which basically states, if

07:20.120 --> 07:25.720
anyone, any organization of any type collects data on European Union citizens, that data needs

07:25.720 --> 07:30.240
to be stored on servers in a European Union member state.

07:30.240 --> 07:34.200
And it's for the exact reason I just mentioned earlier, which is the European Union wants

07:34.200 --> 07:38.240
to make sure that they are properly protecting their citizens data, making sure that the

07:38.240 --> 07:41.360
right privacy controls are applied to that data.

07:41.360 --> 07:44.760
And they can only do that if that data is stored on systems in the EU.

07:44.760 --> 07:49.960
If that data was stored on systems and say the US, then I keep picking on the US here,

07:49.960 --> 07:54.480
because the US is fairly well known to have not having the greatest privacy laws.

07:54.480 --> 07:57.960
They also have this lovely thing called the Patriot Act, which I'm oversimplifying here,

07:57.960 --> 08:04.180
but basically says, if any data trends at the US, even just passes through the US,

08:04.180 --> 08:08.220
which a ton of internet traffic does, then that data is now the property of the US government.

08:08.220 --> 08:09.540
They can do whatever they want with it.

08:09.540 --> 08:13.700
It's not quite that severe, but it's that kind of idea.

08:13.700 --> 08:16.740
So certain countries around the world have said, you know what?

08:16.740 --> 08:20.220
We want to control where this data can be stored.

08:20.220 --> 08:24.020
And we want that data to remain within our country's boundaries.

08:24.020 --> 08:27.020
And that way we can make sure we have proper control of the data.

08:27.020 --> 08:32.860
And so these trans-border data flow laws are often related to personal data, PII personally

08:32.860 --> 08:35.260
identifiable information, but not always.

08:35.260 --> 08:38.980
Certain countries, you know, like Russia, China, for instance, they have these trans-border

08:38.980 --> 08:43.300
data flow laws, and they're trying to make sure that certain state information is not

08:43.300 --> 08:45.540
leaving their physical borders.

08:45.540 --> 08:50.180
So just remember this, trans-border data flow laws, and here's the other names, data residency,

08:50.180 --> 08:51.740
data localization laws.

08:51.740 --> 08:57.660
These are laws that require that data remain within certain physical boundaries.

08:57.660 --> 09:01.220
And of course, the reason this is so pertinent nowadays is that everyone's moving their

09:01.220 --> 09:02.580
data to the cloud.

09:02.580 --> 09:04.580
And when you're storing your data in the cloud, where's the data?

09:04.580 --> 09:06.980
I don't know, somewhere in the cloud.

09:06.980 --> 09:13.220
It's very, very easy to fall a foul of these data residency laws if you're storing data

09:13.220 --> 09:16.460
in the cloud, and you're not careful about exactly where you store it.

09:16.460 --> 09:22.780
Now to be clear, the big cloud service providers, this is why they have data centers spread

09:22.780 --> 09:23.780
around the planet.

09:23.780 --> 09:27.900
They have data centers within the UEU, for instance.

09:27.900 --> 09:31.500
So if you're collecting European citizens data, and you're storing it in the Amazon

09:31.500 --> 09:36.980
cloud, you better make sure that you've configured your data storage location to be in data centers

09:36.980 --> 09:41.460
that are in the EU, so that you can remain in compliance with these laws.

09:41.460 --> 09:46.660
So that's trans-border data flow, data residency, data localization laws, ensuring that data

09:46.660 --> 09:49.140
remains within certain physical boundaries.

09:49.140 --> 09:52.820
It doesn't pass out outside of those boundaries to ensure the protection of the data.

